value.0: The massive lizard is a pack lizard, a beast of burden highly valued by underdark merchants and drow sentries. A pack lizard's steady gait and widely-splayed legs give it a keen sense of balance that is needed for carrying the enormous weight of supplies, and furthermore their ability to maneuver along cavern walls and ceilings makes them excellent mounts for drow patrols. Many drow houses breed entire squadrons of lizard cavalry, ones that are lighter and swifter than this heavier, commoner pack lizard variety. Although the lizards have poor eyesight, their incredible sense of smell, when trained properly, makes them better able to navigate lightless tunnels with a minimal decrease in speed; drow raiders take full advantage of this to surprise their quarry by attacking from cavern ceilings with poisoned crossbow bolts.

Dogma of Callarduran Smoothhands: Callarduran led his chosen people into the deepest depths of the earth so that they might discover the joyous beauty of rubies and other gems. Beware the dangers of Deepearth, and guard against evil races such as the drow who employ any means necessary to seize what is not rightfully theirs. Protect and serve your community. Celebrate the beauty of minerals and gems and understand their value in craft, art, and magic.

You can 'take over' a shop if the sign on it says "closed" or the current shopkeeper isn't in this area. Click the Sign to do so.

Once you have taken over a shop you can use the box/bag/bookpile named "Yourname's Wares" as a showcase. Place the items you want to sell in it. Every item will be given back to you, and a copy will remain in the box. This copy will be deleted when it's taken out of the box by anyone or when you close your shop.

Duergar have a long tradition of crafting that goes back to their days as the rulers of Barakuir. Like the dwarves, the duergar are accomplished craftsmen with an eye for detail. 

Their designs are often pragmatic and eschew the ostentatious decorations of their pinker kin, whom the duergar decry as shameless and wasteful. Duergar artwork is notable for its veneration of bloodshed and cruelty, for these go hand in hand with duergar victories.

Scenes of warfare mark much of their art, sending a clear message to all of the underdark that the duergar are not to be trifled with: fighting strange denizens in the icy caverns near Gracklstugh in -3717 DR, painting the walls with gore spilled from the guts of bear-like quaggoths at Ursandunthar near -2600 DR, and many other smaller conflicts that are nonetheless made great by duergar historians. 

Most controversial in L'Obsul is the pillar depicting the war for Dunspeirrin against the forces of Undreath near -1800 DR; in it, duergar mercilessly butcher thousands of drow and mindflayer overlords in a great cavernous nexus.

Value.value: The duergar have engineered a unique system of getting up and down L'Obsul's shaft. Using the incredible heat from the furnances on the lowest level, the duergar have crafted a system that pumps this heat upwards through a ventilation shaft to control a fan, which in turn works the gears for the crane when the ventilation shaft is opened.
The cage goes up and down when the gears on the crane move. The gears on the crane move when the operator opens a vent. It works.

The duergars' crane system is a feat of technical ingenuity, granted. By recycling the heat from the lower furnaces upwards through a ventilation shaft, an operator can release the pressure from the shaft by releasing a vent into a large fan. When the fan rotates, dispersing the superheated air, the fan's gears turn, lowering or raising the crane. However, there are some significant safety flaws inherent in the design, should any working piece become disabled or the heated air from the furnace prove either too cool to build pressure or so hot the pressure overwhelms the ventilation shaft. You are surprised more accidents have not occurred.

This pale glow is clearly the Faerie Fire spell, an early evocation. Faerie Fire lacks the sting of staring into a normal fire, and so the drow favor it not only for brightening their domains but infusing the atmosphere with rarely perceived colors, especially colors that unsettle or intimidate.
This pale glow has a magical origin in the evocation school. Unlike the harsh light of fire, this light does not irritate the eyes.

This pale glow is clearly the Faerie Fire spell, a simple evocation. Faerie Fire lacks the sting of staring into a normal fire, and so the drow favor it not only for brightening their domains but infusing the atmosphere with rarely perceived colors, especially colors that unsettle or intimidate. Faerie Fire is a common spell to learn amongst drow arcanists, who use it for decorative purposes and for security and hunting purposes. The light of Faerie Fire can be used to outline creatures, obstructing their attempts at obfuscation. Drow of noble blood possess an innate ability to evoke this eerie illumination, giving the children of Lolth all the more reason to revere the ruling caste.

The massive lizard is a pack lizard, a beast of burden highly valued by underdark merchants. A pack lizard is built low to the ground with widely-splayed legs, and its sense of balance allows it to carry an enormous burden upon its backs without any limbs giving way. Although the lizards have poor eyesight, their incredible sense of smell, when trained properly, makes them better able to navigate lightless tunnels with a minimal decrease in speed.

The massive lizard is being used as a pack animal by the merchants. Their bellies are low to the ground like a worm, and their legs are splayed wide; you figure they can bear a great deal of weight without worry of their limbs giving way, which means the merchants have the right idea!

Deep gnome culture is steeped with mysteries that few know anything about. The svirfneblin rarely discuss anything with outsiders, and most outsiders care less about what svirfneblin value and more about the value of svirfneblin. The deep gnomes of L'Obsul value the water in this pool and become especially grim if someone ridicules or defiles the water. It becomes a community effort for the deep gnomes to clean it afterwards, always in preparation for a gathering that takes place every three blooms. At the gathering they observe the water, which reflects small motes of light from phosphorescent mushrooms they cultivate on the shaped stalagmites around the pool. The reflection resembles the surface's nighttime sky with its tiny, burning points of light.

The svirfneblin are protective of this pool and become even more sullen than usual if anyone ridicules or defiles it. Many will gather and work to clean it afterwards, always in preparation for some gathering they have every three blooms or so. At the gathering they just stare at the water like they were in a trance. May be a property of the strange little mushrooms they grow on the shaped stalagmites all around the pool.

Deep gnomes do not share the particulars of their culture with outsiders, and outsiders care less about what svirfneblin value and more about the value of svirfneblin, but their cultural mystique is not unknown to you. This pool is more than just mere limpid bathwater, which explains why the svirfneblin are especially sullen when the duergar ridicule it or an orog pees in it out of spite. It becomes a community effort for the deep gnomes to clean it afterwards, always in preparation for a gathering that takes place every three blooms. This gathering is the Festival of the Star, a sacred observation that revolves around the myth of the Deep Brother Callarduran Smoothhands being a patron for the svirfneblin. In the months leading up to the festival, they cultivate special phosphorescent mushrooms on the stalagmites surrounding the pool, and shape the stalagmites in such a way as to position the mushrooms in such a way that their reflection will resemble the surface night sky.

Though the svirfneblin seem a dreary people to the casual observer, in truth they are industrious and have an appreciation for the natural aesthetic. Deep gnomes shape their living spaces out of the very rock they live in, shaping it with tools or sometimes with their own hands.
The sullen little svirfneblin are pretty uncivilized. Unlike the drow, the duergar, and even some of the orogs, they don't live in finely crafted structures. They just live in caves and in rocks.

Deep gnome architecture is defined moreso by the beauty that already exists in the formation of the stone rather than in the form that can be shaped from the stone. With their innate ability to listen to the rock and the sometime gift of conjuring earth elementals, svirfneblin treat architecture with a muted joy, something that gives them comfort, if not happiness. The highest-ranking members of any one deep gnome clan usually inhabit large stalagmites while the lower-caste svirfs inhabit the surrounding cavern floors and walls.

The deep gnome palate leaves something to be desired. Instead of cooking their meat and mushrooms, they just salt the food heavily to preserve it and eat it when time and appetite permit. As necessity would have it, the Council has ensured that any food provided by the svirfneblin remains unsalted and in raw form to be prepared as desired by the consumer. But the svirfneblin are as masterful at food culture as they are with appraisals, and their grocers have the most varied selection of fungi found in the underdark, along with blindfish and sometimes a deep roth roast.

Most svirf food is oversalted, inedible garbage. Fortunately, the Council has seen to it that the food they produce for the whole of L'Obsul can be enjoyed by normal palates. It has all the staples of the underdark diet: meat and mushrooms.

Deep gnome cuisine is an acquired taste. Because fire produces so much unwanted light and smoke, the svirfneblin prefer to salt their raw food to preserve it and then eat it as time and appetite permit. This makes their cuisine nearly inedible to foreign palates, and all deep gnomes offer to wash away the taste is a popular salty spirit made from fermented fish. The Council has decreed that the svirfneblin will provide raw produce, but will leave the preparation of food to the consumer. In this respect, they are as valued for their food as they are for their appraisals. The average svirfneblin grocer in L'Obsul offers the most varied selection of fungi found in the underdark, along with blindfish and sometimes a deep roth roast or the rare sheep or goat pilfered from the surface. Because of their familiarity with the very stone that makes up the underdark, svirfneblin are some of the underdark's most useful foragers and rangers.

value.0:
A faintly glowing rune is set into a tile on the cavern floor here, the tile almost flush with the rock as to make it unobtrusive but noticable to anyone looking for it. You recognize it as a rune of permanency that maintains an illusion effect devised by the magicians of House Zau'tar. The effect fades and blends the din of the bazaar into a faint background drone while neutralizing the volume of individuals within the effect's radius. To newcomers, the effect can be dissconcerting, as a single step over the effect's threshold turned whispering quiet to raucous noise peppered with auctioneer barking and piper's skirling. To merchants, it is a necessity for trade. It is far preferable not to have to shout while you haggle. 

No such enchantments exist to suppress the smells of the bazaar, an olfactory tapestry redolent of spice, exotic and earthy produce imported from the surface, and, alas, mulled wine long past its time, curing leather, burned frying oil, rothe dung, freshly spilled blood and a thousand other things. Many of the stalls shine with the light of phosphorescent fungus or faerie fire positioned to flatter the vendor's wares and discourage thievery. Security is left to the individual merchant, who hires mercenaries or employs magics to protect his or her interests. There are no guard patrols, no license applications necessary, no routine searches of pack animals brought through the bazaar regularly. 

In times past the Council tried to regulate the bazaar and every time it became less profitable for city coffers and the ruling powers of the city, who themselves often run illicit operations in the bazaar. Only when merchants or criminals go too far and step on the wrong toes does "justice" occur.

The Upperdark here is too close to the surface for the comfort of Lowerdark dwellers. The caverns are alive with more than just the thunderous echo of unregulated trade stretching out as far as the eye can see. Bugs scratch fossorial legs on stone while cave bats search them out with nagging chitters before swooping invisible out of the darkness to eat them. 

A massive geothermal vent between L'Obsul and Mt. Eldfell above infuses the cavern with a temperature several degrees warmer than most of the underdark. Svirfneblin enclaves in the form of massive columns stretching from the floor to the ceiling line the far outskirts. 

The numerous torches and faerie fire effects fill the cavern with a hazy and oppressive illumination that only softens when one stares down great central Shaft and into the cool darkness below, where the tiniest motes of static light flicker.

Value.value: The large gemstone on display here to advertise svirfneblin goods comes as no surprise. The deep gnomes have an obsession with gemstones that can border on the ludicrous, driving them so far as to use gemstones in jewelery, architecture, and even to consume them! Gogondy is a svirfneblin wine made from fermented fungus and powdered rubies, said to give the deep gnomes strange and prophetic dreams.
Svirfneblin have no idea of the value of gemstones. Otherwise, they wouldn't leave them lying around like this for just anyone to walk off with!

Deep gnomes prefer to use copious gemstones in their art and in their architecture. Most svirfneblin make their homes near gemstone veins and dedicate a lot of time and energy to mining them. As such, they make the greatest jewelers and appraisers in the underdark. The obsession is more than just mercantile; to the svirfneblin, it is spiritual. Gogondy is a wine the deep gnomes make from fermented fungus and powdered rubies, said to give them prophetic dreams, and is often used as a ritual component in dedications to their patron deity, Callarduran Smoothhands. You can often find the deity's symbol cut into gemstones they display and trade, but never into rings or bands of gold, a practice considered taboo for reasons esoteric even to you. They believe it was Callarduran who first showed them how to commune with the earth and its elementals, and that he hid all of the worlds rubies in the earth specifically for the svirfneblin to find. To this day the myth is celebrated during the Festival of the Ruby.

Sava is an intricate game representing a war between two drow noble Houses, though the game's proliferation through the underdark and even on the surface has seen it modified to represent other battlefield motifs with pieces unique to the culture in which the game is played. You recall an antique set that recapitulated in miniature the drow's eternal struggle with another race, but such pieces had gone out of fashion long before your birth, probably because nobody wanted to play a dwarf. Each player maneuvers artfully crafted marble pieces on a web-shaped board patterned with squares of alternating colors. 

Each piece - the warrior, the slave, the priestess, and the mage - has specific rules regarding its movement across the board to conquer other pieces. In celebration of the divine chaos in their blood, the drow introduced an element of randomness into a game that would otherwise unfold with mechanical precision: the sava dice. 

Once per game, each player can forego a normal move to throw the sava dice, a pair of round octahedrons. If the results are twin spiders, the player can move an opponent's piece to eliminate another opponent's piece within its normal reach, a rule that acknowledged the prevalence of treachery in drow society.

The Order of the Crouching Lemur are a monastic group who espouse endurance and strength of spirit in the face of adversity, and prove this by eking out an existence on a harsh mountain in the Skull Crags, beset on all sides by the environment and hostile creatures.

Despite their isolationist ways, they are surprisingly welcoming to outsiders, offering fine wares and supplies to those who can provide the coin. It isn't uncommon to find these robes in place as far as Brogendenstein, and this open nature has helped spread the word of the relatively small monastery across the land.

Value.value: The recent skirmish with Wolfpelt's forces within L'Obsul has left its mark on the city - though far more so here on the topmost level than the rest of the city. Several massive stalactites were torn loose from the ceiling during the bombardment from the mid level, the impacts of which left several nearby structures badly damaged, some even shifted slightly off their foundations. Even the bridges spanning the chasm over which L'Obsul straddles seem to have shifted slightly aside, leaving one wondering about their structural integrity.
